arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.
1.42 m north south -by- 2.54 m east west.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 48 is the stairway in the west of the colonnaded corridor, extending into the balk. It is made of four rows of steps, leading south up to the middle of the third course of the Nabataean retaining wall (Locus 2). The steps are made of sandstone pavers with snecking stones as support. The steps have an average height of 24 cm, and the pavers themselves are quite disparately sized. Some of the pavers are roughly hewn, while others are dressed. Two sondages below steps of the stairway show that a rough leveling course was first put down onto which the pavers could rest. Hopefully, study of the finds from within those leveling courses (Locus 68 and Locus 70) will pinpoint a date for the construction of the stairway. The floor at the base of the stairway is nicely fit with the stairway. The meeting of the doorway (Locus 36) at the top of the stairway in Locus 2, however, is not so neat. The stairway meets the wall in the middle of the third row of the wall, and there is no clear threshold in the doorway. The stairway is likely therefore to be part of the construction of the Roman Bath Complex, while the doorway itself is earlier, part of the original construction of Locus 2. The stairway is phased to Stage 2.
